sec.p:
The following assumptions are made for modeling a suspension:10,11


Wheel knuckle, control arms and tie rod are regarded as rigid bodies, and the tire deformation is neglected;

Self-weight of each rigid body is ignored;

Friction and damping in the joints and the shock absorber are neglected;

Forces and torques acting on the tire are varied slowly and regarded as quasi-static.

If a body is rotated from one location to another position, the new orientation of the body can be determined through three successive rotations around three axis of a coordinate system connected with the rigid body, o-xyz. Assuming rotation angles around z-, y- and x-axis are γ, β and α, respectively, the new coordinates for points M and N in the rigid body in the fixed coordinate system body, {M*} and {N*}, can be estimated using
(2){M*}=[X(α)][Y(β)][Z(γ)]{M0}
(3){N*}=[X(α)][Y(β)][Z(γ)]{N0}
where [Z(γ)], [Y(β)] and [X(α)] are the (3 × 3) rotation matrix obtained from a rotation of a vector through an angle γ, β and α about z-, y- and x-axis of frame o-xyz, respectively; {M0} and {N0} are the initial coordinate of point M and N, respectively.

If a quasi-static external load, {FPg}, is applied to the contacting patch between the tire and the ground, the bushings will undergo rotation and translation. The displacements for a bushing, s (s may be A, B, E or F), in GCS are calculated by
(11){QSg}={{S*}-{S0}{φS}}+{{ΔS0g}{ΔφS0g}}
where superscript g denotes that the values are defined in GCS; {φS} is the rotational angles of bushing s in GCS under the input load.

In the similarly way, the forces and moments applied to the lower control arms in GCS from the reaction forces and moments of bushing Sl (Sl can be E or F) are
(19){{RFSlg}{RMSlg}}=[I,0[R~SlG*],I]{-{FSlg}-{MSlg}}
where the [R~SlG*] in equation (11) is the (3 × 3) skew-symmetric matrix of the position vector for bushing Sl.

Under the reaction forces and moments from the bushings and spring, and ball joints in the wheel knuckle, the upper control arm is in equilibrium status. So the sum of each force components of all forces, and the sum of each moment components from each force about the ball point D in the GCS are zero. According to this principle, one can get the static equilibrium equation for the upper control arm and is expressed as
(20){{RFAg}{RMAg}}+{{RFBg}{RMBg}}+{{FCg}{MCg}}+{{FDg}0}={0}
where {FDg} is the joint forces applied to the upper control arm from the wheel knuckle at ball joint D; and {FCg} is the reaction force applied to the upper control arm from the spring, and is calculated with
(21){FCg}=fs2{RCI*}
where fs2 is the scale factor used to describe the reaction force from spring to upper control arm at ball joint C, and {RCI*} is the position vector from point I to point C. The {MCg} in equation (20) is the moment of {FCg} to ball joint D.

In the similar way for getting static equilibrium equation for upper control arm, one can get the static equilibrium equation for the lower control arm and is expressed as
(22){{RFEg}{RMEg}}+{{RFFg}{RMFg}}+{{FGg}0}={0}
where {FGg} is the reaction forces applied to the lower control arm from the wheel knuckle at Joint G.

A wheel knuckle is in equilibrium status under the reaction forces and moments from the upper and lower control arms, the tie rod, and the external load at tire contact patch, so one can get the static equilibrium equation and is expressed as
(23){{FPg}{MPg}}-{{FDg}{MDg}}-{{FHg}{MHg}}-{{FGg}0}={0}
where {FPg} is the external force applied to the tire contact patch from the road, and {MPg} is the reaction moment from {FPg} about ball joint G; {FDg} is the reaction forces from ball joint D, and {MDg} is the reaction moment of {FDg} about ball joint G.

The {FHg} in equation (23) is the reaction force applied to the wheel knuckle from the tie rod, and is expressed as
(24){FHg}=fs1{RJH*}
where fs1 is the scale factor, and {RJH*} is a vector from point H to point J. The {MHg} is the moment resulting from {FHg} to ball Joint G.
